"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have not found a case in which Bazza can force a win.  \nFor every positive real number \\(\\lambda>0\\) Alice possesses a winning strategy; for \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game can never end, so neither player wins.\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \nThe game is analysed by looking at the two constraints that are active on the even turns:\n\n* After Alice\u2019s move on turn \\(2k-1\\) the total sum of squares is  \n  \\[\n  S_{2k-1}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i^{2}.\n  \\]\n  Bazza must then choose a non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) with  \n  \\[\n  S_{2k}=S_{2k-1}+x_{2k}^{2}\\le 2k .\n  \\]\n  Hence Bazza loses exactly when Alice can make \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\).\n\n* Alice\u2019s own restriction is a bound on the ordinary sum:  \n  \\[\n  \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i\\le \\lambda(2k-1).\n  \\]\n\n  For a fixed total ordinary sum, the sum of squares is maximised by concentrating the whole sum in a single term (convexity of \\(t\\mapsto t^{2}\\)).  \n  Consequently Alice can, on her \\((2k-1)\\)-st turn, set all her previous odd\u2011turn numbers to \\(0\\) and choose  \n  \\[\n  x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1).\n  \\]\n  This yields  \n  \\[\n  S_{2k-1}= \\bigl(\\lambda(2k-1)\\bigr)^{2}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}.\n  \\]\n\n* Alice wins as soon as she can make  \n  \\[\n  \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k .\n  \\tag{1}\n  \\]\n  For any fixed \\(\\lambda>0\\) the left\u2011hand side of (1) grows like \\(k^{2}\\) while the right\u2011hand side grows only linearly; therefore (1) holds for all sufficiently large \\(k\\).  \n  Explicitly, (1) is satisfied whenever  \n  \\[\n  \\lambda>\\frac{\\sqrt{2k}}{\\,2k-1\\,}.\n  \\]\n  The right\u2011hand side tends to \\(0\\) as \\(k\\to\\infty\\), so for every \\(\\lambda>0\\) we can pick a large enough integer \\(k\\) that makes (1) true.\n\n* Throughout the preceding turns Alice keeps the square sum below the even\u2011turn bound by playing \\(x_{2j-1}=0\\) for \\(j<k\\); Bazza can always answer with \\(x_{2j}=0\\). Thus Bazza never runs out of a legal move before the decisive turn.\n\n* If \\(\\lambda=0\\) Alice is forced to choose \\(x_n=0\\) for every turn, so the square sum stays \\(0\\) forever and the game never terminates; consequently neither player wins.\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet the game start with \\(n=1\\).  \nFor each integer \\(k\\ge 1\\) denote by  \n\n\\[\nA_{k}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i ,\\qquad   \nS_{2k-1}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i^{2}\n\\]\n\nthe cumulative ordinary sum after Alice\u2019s \\((2k-1)\\)-st move and the cumulative sum of squares after that move, respectively.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma 1  \nIf after Alice\u2019s move on turn \\(2k-1\\) we have \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\), then Bazza has no legal choice for \\(x_{2k}\\) and loses.\n\n*Proof.* Bazza must choose a non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) satisfying  \n\n\\[\nS_{2k}=S_{2k-1}+x_{2k}^{2}\\le 2k .\n\\]\n\nIf \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\) the inequality cannot hold for any real \\(x_{2k}\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n### Lemma 2  \nFor a fixed ordinary sum \\(A\\ge 0\\) the quantity \\(\\sum_{i}x_i^{2}\\) is maximised when all of the sum is placed in a single term, i.e. when one \\(x_i=A\\) and the others are \\(0\\).\n\n*Proof.* The function \\(t\\mapsto t^{2}\\) is convex on \\([0,\\infty)\\). By Jensen\u2019s inequality, for non\u2011negative numbers \\(y_1,\\dots ,y_m\\) with \\(\\sum y_i=A\\),\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i^{2}\\le m\\Bigl(\\frac{A}{m}\\Bigr)^{2}= \\frac{A^{2}}{m}\\le A^{2},\n\\]\n\nand equality is attained when exactly one \\(y_i=A\\) and the rest are \\(0\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n### Construction of Alice\u2019s winning strategy ( \\(\\lambda>0\\) )\n\nFix \\(\\lambda>0\\). Choose an integer \\(k\\) large enough that  \n\n\\[\n\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k . \\tag{2}\n\\]\n\nSuch a \\(k\\) exists because the left\u2011hand side of (2) grows quadratically in \\(k\\) whereas the right\u2011hand side grows linearly.\n\nAlice proceeds as follows.\n\n* For the first \\(k-1\\) odd turns (\\(n=1,3,\\dots ,2k-3\\)) she plays \\(x_n=0\\).  \n  Consequently after each of these turns \\(A_{j}=0\\) and \\(S_{2j-1}=0\\).\n\n* On her decisive turn \\(n=2k-1\\) she plays  \n\n\\[\nx_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1).\n\\]\n\n  This is allowed because the ordinary sum after the move equals  \n\n  \\[\n  A_{k}= \\lambda(2k-1)\\le \\lambda(2k-1),\n  \\]\n\n  i.e. it meets Alice\u2019s constraint exactly.\n\n  By Lemma\u202f2 the resulting sum of squares is maximal and equals  \n\n  \\[\n  S_{2k-1}=x_{2k-1}^{2}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}.\n  \\]\n\n  By the choice of \\(k\\), inequality (2) holds, so \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\).\n\nAt this point Lemma\u202f1 applies: Bazza cannot choose any non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) satisfying his bound, and therefore loses. Hence Alice wins.\n\n---\n\n### Analysis of the case \\(\\lambda=0\\)\n\nIf \\(\\lambda=0\\), Alice\u2019s rule forces \\(x_n=0\\) for every odd \\(n\\). Consequently all squares remain zero, so for every even \\(n\\) the inequality  \n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_i^{2}\\le n\n\\]\n\nholds with equality \\(0\\le n\\). Bazza can always answer with \\(x_n=0\\). The game therefore continues indefinitely; no player ever wins.\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\n\n* For every \\(\\lambda>0\\) Alice has a winning strategy, described above.\n* For \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game never terminates, so neither player wins.\n* Bazza never has a winning strategy for any \\(\\lambda\\ge 0\\) because he can always respond with \\(x_{2k}=0\\) as long as the square sum does not already exceed his bound, and Alice can avoid exceeding it until she deliberately forces a win.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Alice wins for all }\\lambda>0;\\; \\text{no value of }\\lambda\\text{ gives Bazza a winning strategy.}}\n\\]"
