"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have a complete solution.  \n- For every \\(\\lambda>0\\) Alice has a winning strategy.  \n- For \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game never terminates, so neither player wins.  \n- There is no value of \\(\\lambda\\) for which Bazza can force a win.\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \nThe game is examined at the even turns, because Bazza loses exactly when the cumulative sum of squares after Alice\u2019s preceding odd turn exceeds the even\u2011turn bound.\n\n*Notation.* After Alice\u2019s \\((2k-1)\\)-st move let  \n\n\\[\nA_{k}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i ,\\qquad   \nS_{2k-1}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i^{2}.\n\\]\n\n*Key observations*  \n\n1. **Lemma\u202f1.** If \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\) then Bazza cannot choose any non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) satisfying his constraint, so he loses.  \n\n2. **Lemma\u202f2.** For a fixed ordinary sum \\(A\\ge0\\) the sum of squares \\(\\sum x_i^{2}\\) is maximised when the whole sum is placed in a single term (convexity of \\(t\\mapsto t^{2}\\)).  \n\nUsing Lemma\u202f2, Alice can make the square sum as large as possible by concentrating all of her allowed ordinary sum into the current odd turn. On turn \\(2k-1\\) she may set  \n\n\\[\nx_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1),\n\\]\n\nwhich respects her bound exactly and yields  \n\n\\[\nS_{2k-1}= \\bigl(\\lambda(2k-1)\\bigr)^{2}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}.\n\\]\n\nShe wins as soon as  \n\n\\[\n\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k . \\tag{\u2605}\n\\]\n\nFor any fixed \\(\\lambda>0\\) the left\u2011hand side of (\u2605) grows like \\(k^{2}\\) while the right\u2011hand side grows linearly, so (\u2605) holds for all sufficiently large \\(k\\).  \n\nAlice\u2019s concrete strategy: play \\(x_{2j-1}=0\\) for the first \\(k-1\\) odd turns, then on turn \\(2k-1\\) play \\(x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1)\\). Bazza can always answer with \\(x_{2j}=0\\) until the decisive turn, where Lemma\u202f1 forces his loss.  \n\nIf \\(\\lambda=0\\) Alice is forced to choose \\(0\\) each time, the square sum stays \\(0\\) forever, and the game never ends; thus no player wins.\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet the game start with turn \\(n=1\\).  \nFor each integer \\(k\\ge1\\) define  \n\n\\[\nA_{k}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i ,\\qquad   \nS_{2k-1}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i^{2},\n\\]\n\nthe cumulative ordinary sum and the cumulative sum of squares after Alice\u2019s \\((2k-1)\\)-st move.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma 1  \nIf after Alice\u2019s move on turn \\(2k-1\\) we have \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\), then Bazza has no legal choice for \\(x_{2k}\\) and loses.\n\n*Proof.* Bazza must choose a non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) satisfying  \n\n\\[\nS_{2k}=S_{2k-1}+x_{2k}^{2}\\le 2k .\n\\]\n\nIf \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\) the inequality cannot hold for any real \\(x_{2k}\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n### Lemma 2  \nFor a fixed ordinary sum \\(A\\ge0\\) the quantity \\(\\sum_{i}x_i^{2}\\) is maximised when all of the sum is placed in a single term, i.e. when one \\(x_i=A\\) and the others are \\(0\\).\n\n*Proof.* The map \\(t\\mapsto t^{2}\\) is convex on \\([0,\\infty)\\). For non\u2011negative numbers \\(y_1,\\dots ,y_m\\) with \\(\\sum y_i=A\\),\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i^{2}\\le m\\Bigl(\\frac{A}{m}\\Bigr)^{2}= \\frac{A^{2}}{m}\\le A^{2},\n\\]\n\nand equality occurs precisely when one \\(y_i=A\\) and the rest are \\(0\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n### Alice\u2019s winning strategy for \\(\\lambda>0\\)\n\nFix \\(\\lambda>0\\). Choose an integer \\(k\\) large enough that  \n\n\\[\n\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k . \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nSuch a \\(k\\) exists because the left\u2011hand side of (1) grows quadratically in \\(k\\) whereas the right\u2011hand side grows linearly.\n\nAlice proceeds as follows.\n\n1. **First \\(k-1\\) odd turns** (\\(n=1,3,\\dots ,2k-3\\)): set \\(x_n=0\\).  \n   Then after each of these turns \\(A_{j}=0\\) and \\(S_{2j-1}=0\\), so both players\u2019 constraints are satisfied.\n\n2. **Decisive odd turn** (\\(n=2k-1\\)): set  \n\n   \\[\n   x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1).\n   \\]\n\n   This choice respects Alice\u2019s rule because  \n\n   \\[\n   \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i = \\lambda(2k-1)\\le \\lambda(2k-1).\n   \\]\n\n   By Lemma\u202f2 the resulting sum of squares is maximal and equals  \n\n   \\[\n   S_{2k-1}=x_{2k-1}^{2}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}.\n   \\]\n\n   By the choice of \\(k\\), inequality (1) holds, so \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\).\n\nAt this moment Lemma\u202f1 applies: Bazza cannot find any non\u2011negative \\(x_{2k}\\) satisfying his bound, and therefore loses. Hence Alice wins.\n\n---\n\n### The case \\(\\lambda=0\\)\n\nIf \\(\\lambda=0\\), Alice\u2019s rule forces \\(x_n=0\\) for every odd \\(n\\). Consequently all squares remain zero, so for every even \\(n\\)\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_i^{2}=0\\le n .\n\\]\n\nBazza can always answer with \\(x_n=0\\). The game therefore continues indefinitely; no player ever wins.\n\n---\n\n### Impossibility of a Bazza winning strategy\n\nFor any \\(\\lambda\\ge0\\) Bazza can always keep the game alive by replying with \\(x_{2j}=0\\) as long as the square sum does not already exceed his bound. Alice\u2019s strategy above shows that, when \\(\\lambda>0\\), she can force a turn where the square sum exceeds the bound, making Bazza lose. When \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game never ends, so Bazza also cannot force a win. Hence there is no \\(\\lambda\\) for which Bazza has a winning strategy.\n\n---\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Alice wins for every }\\lambda>0;\\; \\text{for }\\lambda=0\\text{ the game never terminates; Bazza never has a winning strategy.}}\n\\]"
