"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **invalid** because it contains a **Justification Gap** in the proof of Lemma\u202f2 (the argument for the maximality of the sum of squares is incorrect).\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** \u201c*For a fixed ordinary sum \\(A\\ge0\\) the quantity \\(\\sum_{i}x_i^{2}\\) is maximised when all of the sum is placed in a single term\u2026*\u201d (Lemma\u202f2).\n  * **Issue:** **Justification Gap** \u2013 the provided inequality \\(\\sum y_i^{2}\\le m\\bigl(\\frac{A}{m}\\bigr)^{2}= \\frac{A^{2}}{m}\\le A^{2}\\) is false; the direction of the inequality is reversed, so the argument does not rigorously establish the claimed maximality.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n---\n\n#### Step 1 \u2013 Definitions  \n\n> \u201cFor each integer \\(k\\ge1\\) define  \n> \\[\n> A_{k}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i ,\\qquad   \n> S_{2k-1}= \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1} x_i^{2},\n> \\]\u201d\n\n*Correct.* These are clear definitions of the cumulative ordinary sum and cumulative sum of squares after Alice\u2019s \\((2k-1)\\)-st move.\n\n---\n\n#### Step 2 \u2013 Lemma\u202f1  \n\n> \u201cIf after Alice\u2019s move on turn \\(2k-1\\) we have \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\), then Bazza has no legal choice for \\(x_{2k}\\) and loses.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* Bazza must satisfy \\(S_{2k}=S_{2k-1}+x_{2k}^{2}\\le 2k\\). If \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\) the inequality is impossible for any real \\(x_{2k}\\ge0\\). The proof is straightforward.\n\n---\n\n#### Step 3 \u2013 Lemma\u202f2 (Problematic)  \n\n> \u201cFor a fixed ordinary sum \\(A\\ge0\\) the quantity \\(\\sum_{i}x_i^{2}\\) is maximised when all of the sum is placed in a single term, i.e. when one \\(x_i=A\\) and the others are \\(0\\).  \n> *Proof.* The map \\(t\\mapsto t^{2}\\) is convex on \\([0,\\infty)\\). For non\u2011negative numbers \\(y_1,\\dots ,y_m\\) with \\(\\sum y_i=A\\),  \n> \\[\n> \\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i^{2}\\le m\\Bigl(\\frac{A}{m}\\Bigr)^{2}= \\frac{A^{2}}{m}\\le A^{2},\n> \\]  \n> and equality occurs precisely when one \\(y_i=A\\) and the rest are \\(0\\).\u201d\n\n**Issue \u2013 Justification Gap.**  \nThe inequality written is **incorrect**. For non\u2011negative numbers with fixed sum \\(A\\),\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{m}\\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i^{2}\\;\\ge\\;\\Bigl(\\frac{1}{m}\\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i\\Bigr)^{2}\n\\]\n\nby Jensen\u2019s inequality (or by the Cauchy\u2013Schwarz inequality), i.e.\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{m} y_i^{2}\\;\\ge\\;\\frac{A^{2}}{m}.\n\\]\n\nThus the direction \u201c\\(\\le\\)\u201d in the solution is false. The correct statement that the **maximum** of \\(\\sum y_i^{2}\\) under the constraint \\(\\sum y_i=A\\) is \\(A^{2}\\) (attained when one term equals \\(A\\) and the rest are zero) is true, but the argument given does not establish it. A proper proof would argue that moving any positive amount from a smaller term to a larger term increases the sum of squares, leading to the extremal configuration with a single non\u2011zero term. Because the provided justification is invalid, this step contains a gap in rigor.\n\n*We will assume the conclusion of Lemma\u202f2 (the maximal sum of squares equals \\(A^{2}\\)) is true for the purpose of checking the remaining steps.*\n\n---\n\n#### Step 4 \u2013 Alice\u2019s winning strategy for \\(\\lambda>0\\)\n\n> \u201cFix \\(\\lambda>0\\). Choose an integer \\(k\\) large enough that \\(\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k\\). \u2026  \n> 1. First \\(k-1\\) odd turns: set \\(x_n=0\\).  \n> 2. Decisive odd turn \\(n=2k-1\\): set \\(x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1)\\).\u201d\n\n*Correct (assuming Lemma\u202f2).*\n\n- The inequality \\(\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k\\) can indeed be satisfied for sufficiently large \\(k\\) because the left side grows like \\(k^{2}\\) while the right side grows like \\(k\\).\n- Setting the first \\(k-1\\) odd moves to zero keeps both players\u2019 constraints satisfied.\n- At turn \\(2k-1\\) the ordinary\u2011sum constraint is met with equality:\n  \\[\n  \\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i = \\lambda(2k-1) \\le \\lambda(2k-1).\n  \\]\n- By the (assumed) Lemma\u202f2, the sum of squares after this move is maximised and equals\n  \\[\n  S_{2k-1}=x_{2k-1}^{2}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k.\n  \\]\n\nThus the conditions of Lemma\u202f1 are satisfied, forcing Bazza to lose. The reasoning is sound provided Lemma\u202f2\u2019s conclusion holds.\n\n---\n\n#### Step 5 \u2013 The case \\(\\lambda=0\\)\n\n> \u201cIf \\(\\lambda=0\\), Alice\u2019s rule forces \\(x_n=0\\) for every odd \\(n\\). Consequently all squares remain zero\u2026 the game continues indefinitely.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* With all moves zero, both constraints are always satisfied, so the game never ends and no player wins.\n\n---\n\n#### Step 6 \u2013 Impossibility of a Bazza winning strategy\n\n> \u201cFor any \\(\\lambda\\ge0\\) Bazza can always keep the game alive by replying with \\(x_{2j}=0\\)\u2026 Hence there is no \\(\\lambda\\) for which Bazza has a winning strategy.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* If Bazza could force a win, he would need to make Alice eventually unable to satisfy her sum constraint. However, Alice\u2019s strategy (for \\(\\lambda>0\\)) already guarantees a win for her, and for \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game never ends. Therefore Bazza never has a winning strategy.\n\n---\n\n#### Conclusion  \n\nAll steps after Lemma\u202f2 are logically sound **provided** the statement of Lemma\u202f2 is true. The solution\u2019s proof of Lemma\u202f2 contains an incorrect inequality, leaving a **Justification Gap**. Because the gap is not filled, the solution does not meet the required standard of rigor. Hence the overall solution is deemed invalid."
