ginal sum cannot exceed the final value \\(A^{2}\\). Equality occurs only when no merging is needed, i.e. when exactly one term is non\u2011zero.  \n\n  This argument is a standard \u201cconvexity\u201d proof and is fully rigorous.\n\n*Conclusion:* Lemma\u202f2 is correctly proved.\n\n---\n\n#### 4. Existence of a suitable \\(k\\) for \\(\\lambda>0\\)\n\n> \u201cBecause \\(\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}\\) grows like \\(k^{2}\\) while \\(2k\\) grows like \\(k\\), there exists an integer \\(k\\) such that  \n> \\[\n> \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k .\n> \\]\u201d\n\n*Justification:* For any fixed \\(\\lambda>0\\), the left\u2011hand side is a quadratic polynomial in \\(k\\) with positive leading coefficient \\(\\lambda^{2}4\\), while the right\u2011hand side is linear. Hence the inequality holds for all sufficiently large \\(k\\). This is a standard growth\u2011argument and is acceptable at IMO level.\n\n*Conclusion:* The existence claim is valid.\n\n---\n\n#### 5. Alice\u2019s strategy for \\(\\lambda>0\\)\n\n**Step\u202f5.1 \u2013 First \\(k-1\\) odd turns:**  \n\n> \u201cSet \\(x_n=0\\). Then after each of these turns \\(A_{j}=0\\) and \\(S_{2j-1}=0\\); both players\u2019 constraints are satisfied.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* Zero choices trivially satisfy the non\u2011negativity and the respective bounds.\n\n**Step\u202f5.2 \u2013 Decisive odd turn \\(n=2k-1\\):**  \n\n> \u201cSet \\(x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1)\\). This respects Alice\u2019s rule because the sum equals the bound. By Lemma\u202f2 the sum of squares is maximal and equals \\(\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k\\).\u201d\n\n*Verification:*  \n- The cumulative ordinary sum after this move is exactly \\(\\lambda(2k-1)\\), which meets the inequality \\( \\le \\lambda n\\) with equality.  \n- By Lemma\u202f2, distributing a total sum \\(A=\\lambda(2k-1)\\) among the first \\(2k-1\\) terms yields a maximal square sum of \\(A^{2}\\), attained when the entire amount is placed in a single term\u2014precisely what Alice does. Hence \\(S_{2k-1}