s like \\(k^{2}\\) while \\(2k\\) grows like \\(k\\), there exists an integer \\(k\\) such that  \n> \\[\n> \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k .\n> \\]\u201d\n\n*Correct.* For fixed \\(\\lambda>0\\), the left\u2011hand side is asymptotic to \\(4\\lambda^{2}k^{2}\\) and dominates the linear right\u2011hand side. Hence a sufficiently large integer \\(k\\) satisfies the inequality.\n\n---\n\n#### 5. Alice\u2019s strategy for \\(\\lambda>0\\)\n\n**Step\u202f5.1 \u2013 First \\(k-1\\) odd turns:**  \n> \u201cSet \\(x_n=0\\). Then after each of these turns \\(A_{j}=0\\) and \\(S_{2j-1}=0\\); both players\u2019 constraints are satisfied.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* Zero choices trivially satisfy the non\u2011negativity and the respective bounds.\n\n**Step\u202f5.2 \u2013 Decisive odd turn \\(n=2k-1\\):**  \n> \u201cSet \\(x_{2k-1}= \\lambda(2k-1)\\). This respects Alice\u2019s rule because the total sum equals \\(\\lambda(2k-1)\\). By Lemma\u202f2 the resulting sum of squares is maximal and equals \\(\\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}>2k\\).\u201d\n\n*Correct.*  \n- The sum constraint is exactly saturated: \\(\\sum_{i=1}^{2k-1}x_i = \\lambda(2k-1) \\le \\lambda(2k-1)\\).  \n- Lemma\u202f2 guarantees that, among all ways to distribute the total ordinary sum \\(\\lambda(2k-1)\\) over the first \\(2k-1\\) terms, placing it all in a single term maximises the square sum, giving \\(S_{2k-1}= \\lambda^{2}(2k-1)^{2}\\).  \n- By the choice of \\(k\\) we have \\(S_{2k-1}>2k\\).\n\n**Step\u202f5.3 \u2013 Consequence:**  \n> \u201cLemma\u202f1 applies, so Bazza cannot choose a legal \\(x_{2k}\\) and loses.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* Direct application of Lemma\u202f1.\n\nThus Alice indeed has a winning strategy for every \\(\\lambda>0\\).\n\n---\n\n#### 6. The case \\(\\lambda=0\\)\n\n> \u201cAlice is forced to choose \\(x_n=0\\) on every odd turn, so all squares remain zero. Bazza can always answer with \\(x_n=0\\). The game continues indefinitely; no player ever wins.\u201d\n\n*Correct.* With \\(\\lambda=0\\) the odd\u2011turn bound forces all odd\u2011indexed \\(x_n\\) to be zero, and the even\u2011turn bound is never violated by choosing zero. Hence the game never terminates.\n\n---\n\n#### 7. Non\u2011existence of a Bazza winning strategy\n\n> \u201cFor any \\(\\lambda\\ge0\\) Bazza can keep the game alive by replying with \\(x_{2j}=0\\) as long as the square sum does not already exceed his bound. Alice\u2019s strategy above shows that, when \\(\\lambda>0\\), she can force a turn where the square sum exceeds the bound, making Bazza lose. When \\(\\lambda=0\\) the game never ends, so Bazza also cannot force a win. Hence there is no \\(\\lambda\\) for which Bazza has a winning strategy.\u201d\n\n*Correct.*  \n- If \\(\\lambda>0\\), Alice\u2019s explicit winning strategy guarantees Bazza\u2019s loss, so Bazza cannot have a winning strategy.  \n- If \\(\\lambda=0\\), the game is infinite regardless of Bazza\u2019s actions, so Bazza cannot force a win either.  \n- The statement \u201cBazza can keep the game alive by replying with \\(x_{2j}=0\\)\u201d is a valid defensive move; it does not contradict the existence of Alice\u2019s winning strategy.\n\n---\n\n#### 8. Final conclusion\n\n> \u201c\\[\n> \\boxed{\\text{Alice wins for every }\\lambda>0;\\; \\text{for }\\lambda=0\\text{ the game never terminates; Bazza never has a winning strategy.}}\n> \\]\u201d\n\n*Correct.* This succinctly summarizes the verified results.\n\n--- \n\n**Overall Assessment:** Every claim in the solution is supported by a rigorous argument; no logical fallacies, calculation errors, or unjustified steps are present. Consequently, the solution is fully valid."
